    <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/965-1981-1040" data-comment-wp-id="1040" class="comment level0 calledOut">
    	<div class="user_block">
						<!-- Comment ID is comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/965-1981-1040 -->
            <!-- Integer Comment ID is 1040 -->
			<!-- Comment parent ID is $comment.parentCommentId -->
			<!-- Comment publishDate is Sat Aug 27 12:52:21 EDT 2011 -->
			
							<a class="avatar">
					<img src="http://blogs-images.forbes.com/cache/gravatars/e41fa943de4448797a4617ea45d93da5_136.jpg" alt="gslusher" />
				</a>
						
							<a class="user_name nohover">gslusher</a>
			    		
    		
    		
    		
    		
    		
    		    		<span class="timestamp">4 hours ago</span>
    	</div>
    
    	<div class="comment_content">
    		<p>Interesting, but written by someone who, apparently, has never been a leader of anything. Of course, the author is really no worse than the people who write the books he refers to: most of them haven&#8217;t been leaders, either. Those who have often mistake &#8220;my way&#8221; for &#8220;THE way.&#8221;</p>
<p>There are NO &#8220;rules&#8221; of leadership. Every effective leader has her/his own style. Some are tyrannical, some are soft and fuzzy, some are micromanagers, some are &#8220;laissez faire&#8221; (get good people and get out of their way). Different situations demand different styles. George Patton was very effective in North Africa, where he operated pretty much on his own, but he was passed over for the Supreme Allied Commander for Eisenhower, who had much less combat experience but was a diplomat who could keep a lid on Patton, light a fire under Montgomery and keep Churchill and Roosevelt happy. Ike and Patton both inspired their troops, but in different ways for different reasons. Who was the &#8220;better&#8221; leader? Both. Their consistent successes in their situations show that.</p>
<p>Disclaimer: I spent 22 years as an officer in the US military. My leadership style was more the &#8220;laissez faire&#8221; method, which worked in the situations I faced, where I consistently had very smart and dedicated subordinates. It would NOT have worked in many others.</p>

    	</div>
    	
