    <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/965-1981-1042" data-comment-wp-id="1042" class="comment level0 calledOut">
    	<div class="user_block">
						<!-- Comment ID is comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/965-1981-1042 -->
            <!-- Integer Comment ID is 1042 -->
			<!-- Comment parent ID is $comment.parentCommentId -->
			<!-- Comment publishDate is Sat Aug 27 15:38:39 EDT 2011 -->
			
							<a class="avatar">
					<img src="http://blogs-images.forbes.com/cache/gravatars/8cd47e2d1d09ab1245e81841d3f9f5fd_136.jpg" alt="lazyposter" />
				</a>
						
							<a class="user_name nohover">lazyposter</a>
			    		
    		
    		
    		
    		
    		
    		    		<span class="timestamp">1 hour ago</span>
    	</div>
    
    	<div class="comment_content">
    		<p>Gslusher hit the general issue square on the head, an excellent post. Let us look at the specifics.</p>
<p>A corporation or a business is NOT and CANNOT be a democracy. A CEO or an owner is indeed and necessarily be a dictator. Is there a business that sets corporate policies, strategies and tactics by majority vote? Any?</p>
<p>The claim of micromanagement is often misused. A demanding leader demanding higher standards from subordinates needs to articulate that standard clearly. That could mean demanding that a certain things are done a certain specific way at the lowest level. That is not micromanagement, it is communication. As soon as the subordinate gets up to speed and a level of trust is reached, that leader moves on.</p>
<p>As for calling an idea &#8220;dumb&#8221;, it depends on the context. If I know my team really well, I will mince no words. Everyone knows me well enough to not take offense. If I had provided context before the meeting with clear questions expecting everyone to be ready at the meeting and someone comes up with something that is below the lowest expectation, then it is &#8220;dumb&#8221;. In a high-pressure environment, there is no time to mince words. It is not pleasant, may be impolite but the person proposing the idea should have done his or her homework, right?</p>
<p>Relying on instinct? Or is it visions and experience? To an outsider who never really catches on to a person&#8217;s thinking and strategy, it may seem like instinct or intuition. It is all a matter of how much one cares. A professional who takes initiatives and really cares can spent nights, days and hours on end thinking deeply on certain issues resulting in many practical insights. He or she has done the decision tree in his or her head and came up with a simple but elegant solution. Another person who either lacks the initiative or the information to be able to construct a similar decision tree will not be able to arrive at the same or similar conclusion. It is NOT all instinct or intuition. It is actually hard work.</p>
<p>Until you all have been in the trenches and have done it, it is near impossible to &#8220;talk&#8221; about it.</p>

    	</div>
    	
